    <h3 class="apn-r-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">How your gaps interact.</h3>
    <p class="apn-r-body">
      Performance gaps rarely exist in isolation. Sleep deprivation (below 7 hours) raises cortisol by 15 to 20% on average, which directly impairs recovery between training sessions and increases muscle protein breakdown. If recovery is your second gap, sleep is making it worse. If nutrition is involved, inadequate protein intake combined with poor sleep means muscle protein synthesis is being triggered less frequently and less effectively. Fixing your primary gap does not just help that pillar. It reduces the drag on everything else.
