<!-- ===================== MODULE 4: THE ROOKIE PRIORITY FRAMEWORK ===================== -->
<div class="apn-r-module apn-r-module--bg2" id="apn-r-module4">
  <div class="apn-r-wrap">
    <span class="apn-r-section-label">The Framework</span>
    <h2 class="apn-r-h2">The Rookie Priority Framework.</h2>
    <div class="apn-r-divider"></div>

    <p class="apn-r-body">
      Most performance advice is built for athletes who already have a foundation. It assumes consistent sleep, adequate protein, and structured training are already in place. At the Rookie tier, that assumption is wrong. You need a different model.
    </p>

    <h3 class="apn-r-h3" style="margin-top:36px;">The mental model.</h3>
    <p class="apn-r-body" style="font-weight:600; color: var(--black); font-size:18px; line-height:1.5;">
      "One thing. Lock it in. Then add one more."
    </p>
    <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin-top:12px;">
      This is not a shortcut. This is the only approach that builds lasting performance architecture. Adding one behavior at a time until it is automatic, then stacking the next one on top, is how every elite athlete built their foundation. They did not start elite. They started with one locked-in habit and compounded from there. The Rookie who tries to build everything at once builds nothing. The Rookie who locks in one thing every week for four weeks has four real habits at the end of the month.
    </p>

    <div style="margin-top:48px; margin-bottom:48px;">

      <!-- Week 1 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week-header">
          <span class="week-label">Week 1</span>
          <span class="week-title">Sleep Architecture</span>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-week-body">
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin-bottom:16px;"><strong>Focus:</strong> Build the foundation of your recovery system. Nothing else changes this week.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Pick a wake time between 5:30 AM and 7:00 AM. Set it. Hit it every day this week, including Saturday and Sunday. The weekend is where the schedule breaks down for most athletes.</li>
            <li>Target 7 to 8 hours in bed. If you are currently getting 6 or less, move your bedtime back by 30 minutes for the first 3 days, then another 30 minutes for days 4 to 7.</li>
            <li>No screens for 30 minutes before bed. Blue light suppresses melatonin onset by up to 90 minutes according to Harvard Sleep Medicine research. This is not optional if you want the other two points to work.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="apn-r-assignment">
            <span class="assignment-label">Week 1 Assignment</span>
            <p>Write your wake time on a piece of paper and put it next to your bed tonight. Track whether you hit it each day in your phone notes. At the end of 7 days, count how many days out of 7 you executed. Anything below 5 of 7 means sleep is your primary gap and the Week 1 protocol extends into Week 2 before anything else is added.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Week 2 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week-header">
          <span class="week-label">Week 2</span>
          <span class="week-title">Protein Target</span>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-week-body">
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin-bottom:16px;"><strong>Focus:</strong> Hit your daily protein target consistently. Sleep protocol continues from Week 1.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Calculate your target: bodyweight in pounds multiplied by 0.7 to 0.8. A 185-pound athlete targets 130 to 148 grams per day. This is the minimum threshold to support lean mass maintenance and recovery.</li>
            <li>Distribute across 3 to 4 meals or feedings. A single large protein meal does not maximize muscle protein synthesis the way distributed feedings do. The leucine threshold (approximately 2 to 3 grams of leucine per feeding) needs to be hit multiple times per day.</li>
            <li>Track it for all 7 days using a free app (Cronometer or MyFitnessPal). You do not need to track forever. You need 7 days of data to know where your baseline actually is.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="apn-r-assignment">
            <span class="assignment-label">Week 2 Assignment</span>
            <p>Log every meal for 7 days. Calculate your average daily protein. If you hit your target 5 of 7 days or more, you advance to Week 3. If you are not hitting it consistently, identify the single meal where the gap is largest and fix that meal specifically before moving on.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Scripture Block -->
      <div class="apn-r-scripture">
        <p>"Give careful thought to the paths for your feet and be steadfast in all your ways."</p>
        <cite>Proverbs 4:26</cite>
      </div>

      <!-- Week 3 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week-header">
          <span class="week-label">Week 3</span>
          <span class="week-title">Foundation Stack Begins</span>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-week-body">
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin-bottom:16px;"><strong>Focus:</strong> Two products. No more. Sleep and protein protocols continue.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Recharge (Creatine Monohydrate): 5 grams every day. Take it at the same time daily, consistency of timing matters more than specific timing. Creatine increases intramuscular phosphocreatine stores, which improves high-intensity output and supports lean mass gains over time. Over 500 peer-reviewed studies confirm this mechanism. This is the starting point before any other supplement.</li>
            <li>Resilience (Whey Protein Isolate): 25 to 30 grams within 45 minutes post-training. This hits the leucine threshold (approximately 2.5 to 3 grams of leucine per serving of high-quality whey) required to maximally stimulate muscle protein synthesis during the post-exercise window when the rate of synthesis is highest.</li>
            <li>No additional supplements this week. Adding more dilutes focus and makes it harder to know what is working.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="apn-r-assignment">
            <span class="assignment-label">Week 3 Assignment</span>
            <p>Set a daily phone reminder for creatine. Set a second reminder 30 minutes before your usual training end time to prepare your post-training shake. Execute both for 7 consecutive days. Consistency of supplement timing is the entire game at this stage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Week 4 -->
      <div class="apn-r-week">
        <div class="apn-r-week-header">
          <span class="week-label">Week 4</span>
          <span class="week-title">Structured Training Program</span>
        </div>
        <div class="apn-r-week-body">
          <p class="apn-r-body" style="margin-bottom:16px;"><strong>Focus:</strong> Choose one training program and execute it exactly. Sleep, protein, and stack continue.</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Choose one program. Not two. Not a hybrid. One: 3 to 5 days per week, specific exercises, rep ranges, and rest periods written down. If you train MMA or a sport, this is your strength and conditioning program, separate from sport-specific training.</li>
            <li>Log every session. Exercises, sets, reps, and weights. This is not optional. Without a training log, you cannot confirm progressive overload is occurring. Progressive overload is the mechanism that drives adaptation. If it is not tracked, it is guesswork.</li>
            <li>Do not modify the program in Week 4. Execute it as written. Adaptation requires consistent stimulus. You cannot assess a program you have customized before the data exists to justify customization.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="apn-r-assignment">
            <span class="assignment-label">Week 4 Assignment</span>
            <p>On Day 28, review all four weeks. Check: Did you hit your wake time 5 of 7 days on average? Did you hit your protein target 5 of 7 days? Did you take creatine every day? Did you log every training session? Count your execution rate. This number tells you whether you are ready to move to the Athlete tier protocol or whether you need another 4-week block here first.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-r-h3">What the next tier looks like. How long it takes. What it requires.</h3>
    <p class="apn-r-body">
      Athlete-tier performance (score 41 to 65) requires the Rookie foundation to be locked in as habit, not effort. The transition happens when sleep is consistent without trying, protein is a matter of planning not willpower, and training follows a program automatically. Most athletes who execute this 4-week framework consistently see their next quiz score improve by 15 to 25 points. The timeline for a genuine tier transition, behavioral habits fully automated, is typically 8 to 12 weeks of consistent execution. Four weeks builds the foundation. The second block of four cements it.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-r-tier-progress">
      <span class="tier-progress-label">Your Tier Path</span>
      <p style="font-family:var(--font); font-size:14px; color:rgba(255,255,255,0.6); line-height:1.6; margin-bottom:20px;">Every tier above you was built by athletes who executed the fundamentals at this tier first. The path is straight. The work is consistent.</p>
      <div class="apn-r-tier-bar">
        <div class="tier-bar-item">
          <div class="tier-bar-dot tier-bar-dot--active"></div>
          <div class="tier-bar-name tier-bar-name--active">Rookie</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-bar-line"></div>
        <div class="tier-bar-item">
          <div class="tier-bar-dot"></div>
          <div class="tier-bar-name">Athlete</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-bar-line"></div>
        <div class="tier-bar-item">
          <div class="tier-bar-dot"></div>
          <div class="tier-bar-name">Competitor</div>
        </div>
        <div class="tier-bar-line"></div>
        <div class="tier-bar-item">
          <div class="tier-bar-dot"></div>
          <div class="tier-bar-name">Elite</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="font-family:var(--font); font-size:13px; color:rgba(255,255,255,0.4); line-height:1.5;">Retake the quiz after 30 days of executing this framework. Your score is a direct reflection of your current behavioral habits. When the habits change, the score changes.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

